  .log { margin-top:12px; height:140px; overflow:auto; background:#111; color:#b8ffd9; padding:8px; font-family: monospace; font-size:12px; border-radius:6px; }
  .good { color: #155724; background: #d4edda; padding:6px; border-radius:4px; border:1px solid #c3e6cb; }
  .bad { color: #721c24; background: #f8d7da; padding:6px; border-radius:4px; border:1px solid #f5c6cb; }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Progress Bar Concurrency Bug Demo</h2>
<p>Two side-by-side demos: left shows a buggy approach where tasks race when updating a shared percentage variable; right shows a corrected approach that avoids the race. Use "Start" to run a single simulation or "Run 10 times" to see the bug appear more often.</p>

<div class="container">
  <div class="panel" id="leftPanel">
    <div class="title">Buggy Implementation</div>
    <div class="barWrap">
      <div class="bar" id="bugBar"></div>
      <div class="label" id="bugLabel">0%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="startBug">Start</button>
      <button id="runBug10">Run 10 times</button>
      <button id="resetBug">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="explain bad" id="bugExplain">
      Problem: multiple asynchronous tasks read and write the same shared percentage variable without coordination. Race conditions can make the progress jump, skip values, or even exceed 100%.
    </div>
    <div class="log" id="bugLog"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="panel" id="rightPanel">
    <div class="title">Fixed Implementation</div>
    <div class="barWrap">
      <div class="bar" id="fixBar"></div>
      <div class="label" id="fixLabel">0%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="startFix">Start</button>
      <button id="runFix10">Run 10 times</button>
      <button id="resetFix">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="explain good" id="fixExplain">
      Fix: each task reports its own share of work; the aggregator performs a single atomic update (adding the task's contribution). Alternatively, serialize updates or use per-task bookkeeping to avoid overwriting reads from other tasks.
    </div>
    <div class="log" id="fixLog"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
/*
Overview of the simulated workload:
- We simulate N tasks (files/chunks).
- Each task completes after a randomized delay and reports progress.
- Buggy implementation: tasks compute and set globalPercentage by reading it, adding their completed percentage slice, and writing back. Because reads/writes interleave, updates can be lost or duplicated.
- Fixed implementation: each task reports its own contribution, and the aggregator sums contributions to maintain total; updates happen by adding the task's slice in one operation that doesn't rely on a stale read.
*/

// Utility helpers
function rand(msMin, msMax) {
  return msMin + Math.floor(Math.random() * (msMax - msMin + 1));
}
function logTo(el, msg) {
  const p = document.createElement('div');
  p.textContent = msg;
  el.appendChild(p);
  el.scrollTop = el.scrollHeight;
}

// Buggy Implementation
(function() {
  const bar = document.getElementById('bugBar');
  const label = document.getElementById('bugLabel');
  const log = document.getElementById('bugLog');
  const startBtn = document.getElementById('startBug');
  const run10Btn = document.getElementById('runBug10');
  const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetBug');

  let globalPercent = 0;
  let runId = 0;

  function render(pct) {
    const clamped = Math.max(0, Math.min(100, pct));
    bar.style.width = clamped + '%';
    label.textContent = Math.round(pct) + '%';
  }

  function reset() {
    globalPercent = 0;
    runId++;
    render(0);
    log.innerHTML = '';
  }

  function startSingle() {
    reset();
    const thisRun = runId;
    const taskCount = 8;
    // Each task conceptually contributes this share of total progress
    const share = 100 / taskCount;

    logTo(log, 'Starting buggy run with ' + taskCount + ' tasks. each share=' + share.toFixed(2) + '%');

    // Simulate tasks that do some async work then update progress
    for (let i = 0; i < taskCount; i++) {
      // Each task will finish at a random time between 100ms and 1000ms
      const delay = rand(80, 900);

      // To emphasize the race, we use a Promise to do some async work, then a setTimeout that mimics more events,
      // producing multiple reads/writes interleaving.
      // Also, create some micro-steps so each task tries to increment progress in small chunks.
      (function(taskIndex) {
        const steps = 1 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 3); // tasks may update in 1..3 steps
        const perStep = share / steps;

        // Simulate initial async work
        Promise.resolve().then(() => {
          return new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, delay));
        }).then(() => {
          // perform 'steps' updates separated by small random gaps to allow interleaving
          let s = 0;
          function doStep() {
            if (runId !== thisRun) return; // aborted
            // BUG: read-modify-write on shared globalPercent without any synchronization
            const read = globalPercent;
            const newVal = read + perStep;
            // simulate some computation delay to widen the race window
            setTimeout(() => {
              // Another read-modify-write might have happened in between
              globalPercent = newVal;
              logTo(log, '[Task ' + taskIndex + ' step ' + s + '] read ' + read.toFixed(2) + ' -> wrote ' + newVal.toFixed(2));
              render(globalPercent);
              s++;
              if (s < steps) {
                setTimeout(doStep, rand(10, 120));
              }
            }, rand(5, 60));
          }
          doStep();
        });
      })(i);
    }

    // After some time, print final value
    setTimeout(() => {
      logTo(log, 'Final globalPercent (buggy) = ' + globalPercent.toFixed(2));
      if (globalPercent > 100) {
        logTo(log, '!!! Exceeded 100% due to races');
      } else if (Math.round(globalPercent) < 100) {
        logTo(log, 'Warning: did not reach 100% (' + globalPercent.toFixed(2) + '%) — some updates were lost');
      } else {
        logTo(log, 'Reached 100% (maybe by luck)');
      }
    }, 1700);
  }

  startBtn.addEventListener('click', startSingle);
  run10Btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    // Run startSingle repeatedly to make race more observable
    let i = 0;
    function doRun() {
      if (i++ >= 10) return;
      startSingle();
      setTimeout(doRun, 2000);
    }
    doRun();
  });
  resetBtn.addEventListener('click', reset);

  reset();
})();


// Fixed Implementation
(function() {
  const bar = document.getElementById('fixBar');
  const label = document.getElementById('fixLabel');
  const log = document.getElementById('fixLog');
  const startBtn = document.getElementById('startFix');
  const run10Btn = document.getElementById('runFix10');
  const resetBtn = document.getElementById('resetFix');

  let totalPercent = 0;
  let runId = 0;

  function render(pct) {
    const clamped = Math.max(0, Math.min(100, pct));
    bar.style.width = clamped + '%';
    label.textContent = Math.round(pct) + '%';
  }

  function reset() {
    totalPercent = 0;
    runId++;
    render(0);
    log.innerHTML = '';
  }

  function startSingle() {
    reset();
    const thisRun = runId;
    const taskCount = 8;
    const share = 100 / taskCount;

    logTo(log, 'Starting fixed run with ' + taskCount + ' tasks. each share=' + share.toFixed(2) + '%');

    // Approach: each task reports increments to an aggregator.
    // The aggregator updates totalPercent by adding the task's contribution.
    // This eliminates using a stale read to compute the new total.
    // Additionally, we clamp the final value to 100 and track per-task completed state.
    const completed = new Array(taskCount).fill(false);

    // Aggregator function that "atomically" adds contribution.
    function addContribution(delta, source) {
      if (runId !== thisRun) return;
      // In single-threaded JS, this function executes without interleaving until it yields.
      // That means read-add-write here is effectively atomic for our async callbacks.
      totalPercent += delta;
      // guard against tiny floating errors
      if (totalPercent > 100) totalPercent = 100;
      logTo(log, '[Aggregator] added ' + delta.toFixed(2) + '% from ' + source + ' -> total=' + totalPercent.toFixed(2));
      render(totalPercent);
    }

    for (let i = 0; i < taskCount; i++) {
      (function(taskIndex) {
        const delay = rand(80, 900);
        const steps = 1 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 3);
        const perStep = share / steps;

        Promise.resolve().then(() => {
          return new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, delay));
        }).then(() => {
          let s = 0;
          function doStep() {
            if (runId !== thisRun) return;
            // Instead of reading total and computing new total, report the contribution amount
            // to the aggregator which performs the update.
            setTimeout(() => {
              addContribution(perStep, 'Task ' + taskIndex + ' step ' + s);
              s++;
              if (s < steps) {
                setTimeout(doStep, rand(10, 120));
              } else {
                completed[taskIndex] = true;
              }
            }, rand(5, 60));
          }
          doStep();
        });
      })(i);
    }

    // After some time, print final value
    setTimeout(() => {
      logTo(log, 'Final totalPercent (fixed) = ' + totalPercent.toFixed(2));
      if (Math.round(totalPercent) < 100) {
        logTo(log, 'Warning: did not reach 100% (' + totalPercent.toFixed(2) + '%) — maybe tasks were cancelled or rounding issues.');
      } else {
        logTo(log, 'Reached 100%');
      }
    }, 1700);
  }

  startBtn.addEventListener('click', startSingle);
  run10Btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    let i = 0;
    function doRun() {
      if (i++ >= 10) return;
      startSingle();
      setTimeout(doRun, 2000);
    }
    doRun();
  });
  resetBtn.addEventListener('click', reset);

  reset();
})();

// Short explanation panel appended below
(function() {
  const e = document.createElement('div');
  e.style.marginTop = '18px';
  e.innerHTML = '<strong>Explanation:</strong> The buggy version has each task read the current shared percentage, compute newValue = read + contribution, then write newValue. Because many async callbacks interleave, two tasks may read the same "old" value and both write updates based on that old value, causing lost updates (total < 100%) or if steps are sized differently, can even exceed 100%. The fix is to have each task report its own contribution and let a single aggregator add contributions (so updates don\\'t rely on stale reads), or otherwise serialize updates (queue, mutex). In JS, the aggregator pattern leverages the single-threaded event loop so a small function that adds a contribution runs to completion without being preempted by another task. This eliminates the race on stale reads.'
  document.body.appendChild(e);
})();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

Notes on why the bug appears:
- JavaScript is single-threaded, but asynchronous callbacks can interleave. If you implement a read-modify-write across separate asynchronous steps, another callback may mutate the same variable between your read and write.
- The buggy demo intentionally increases the time between reading and writing to make races visible.
- The fix uses an aggregator that accepts contributions (deltas) so updates don't depend on a possibly stale read.

If you want a variant using explicit locking (e.g., a small promise-queue) or visualizations that more dramatically exceed 100%, I can adjust the timing or task counts.

