    <div class="bar-wrap">
      <div class="bar" id="buggyBar">0%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="buggyStart">Start run (6 tasks)</button>
      <button id="buggyMany">Start many tasks (30 tasks)</button>
      <button id="buggyReset">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="explain">
      Explanation (buggy): All tasks read and write the same numeric variable "progress". Each task does something like: read currentProgress, compute newProgress = currentProgress + contribution, then write newProgress. Because tasks interleave, two tasks can read the same currentProgress, both compute updates, and one update will overwrite the other — causing skipped percent values or overshoot.
    </div>
    <div class="log" id="buggyLog"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="card" id="fixedCard">
    <div class="title"><strong>Fixed (atomic updates / per-task contribution)</strong><small class="note">Deterministic and bounded</small></div>
    <div class="bar-wrap">
      <div class="bar" id="fixedBar">0%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="fixedStart">Start run (6 tasks)</button>
      <button id="fixedMany">Start many tasks (30 tasks)</button>
      <button id="fixedReset">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="explain">
      Explanation (fixed): Each task reports its own contribution instead of reading the shared counter. The main updater function receives each contribution and updates the shared total in a single place, preventing lost updates. Another safe approach is to use per-task promises and compute progress from finished-count rather than incrementing a shared numeric patchily.
    </div>
