Explanation (brief):
- The bug happens because operations are not atomic. Each task does: read sharedCounter, compute new value, then write it back. If two tasks read the same old value before either writes, one of their increments is overwritten — lost update.
- Fix approaches demonstrated:
  - Actor (serialized queue): all increment requests are queued and applied one at a time by a single async loop. No two tasks can update concurrently.
  - Mutex (Promise lock): a lightweight promise-based lock chains update operations so only one runs the critical section at a time.

You can change number of tasks, units per task, and the async delay to make the bug more or less likely. The page logs each task's observation and final totals so you can see exactly how updates were lost and how the fixes avoid that.

