Explanation recap:
- The buggy version is intentionally naive: workers read progressValue, compute a new value, then after an arbitrary delay write it back — these operations are not atomic. When interleaved, writes can be lost or overwrite later progress.
- The fixed version serializes updates with a queue so each updater runs with the latest value and commits in order, preventing lost updates and backward jumps.

Run the file multiple times and click Start on the buggy side; you should be able to observe incorrect behavior. If you don't see a break immediately, increase WORKER_COUNT or the random delays to make interleavings more likely.

Below is a single self-contained HTML file you can save and open in a browser. It shows two side-by-side progress bars: the left one contains a deliberately buggy implementation that uses shared mutable state updated by multiple asynchronous tasks (setTimeout) and demonstrates a visual race condition that can leave the bar in an incorrect state. The right one shows a fixed implementation that avoids the race by using a per-task local plan and an atomic update function (using a simple compare-and-swap pattern implemented with a loop and timestamps) to ensure updates are applied consistently.

How the buggy version breaks
- The buggy progress bar stores a single shared "progress" value and lets many asynchronous tasks read, compute, and write it without coordination.
- Each task reads the current progress, computes a new progress (progress + delta), and writes it back after a delay. Because the delays interleave, two tasks can read the same initial value and both write back updates that overwrite each other, so some increments are lost. Visually you can see the progress stall or even decrease briefly if drawing logic isn't careful.
- The demo intentionally increases concurrency and uses staggered timers to make races observable. You should see the buggy bar occasionally jump backward or stop before reaching the final value, or finish too early/late.

How the fixed version works
- The fixed bar avoids lost updates by applying updates via an atomic update function: each update provides a delta and the code retries if the current value changed underfoot. This is similar to compare-and-swap (CAS).
- It also keeps each task's intended contribution separate and applies deltas to the shared state with a synchronous, single-place updater so that no intermediate reads of stale state cause lost updates.
- The result is stable, deterministic progression even under the same interleaving of timers.

